{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1676"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.23,0.02,0.01,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1676"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94804"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"627"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49544"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-year-old girl is brought to the General Practice clinic because her mother is concerned about a lesion at the back of her right ear (Image). The lesion appeared soon after birth, got larger and more recently has slowly softened and decreased in size. However, she remains concerned that the child might get teased about this at school. Otherwise, her history reveals no developmental, social or physical abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance, parental education and monitoring","Beta-blockers","Punch biopsy","Shave biopsy","Surgical excision"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Einfantile\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapillary haemangioma (strawberry naevus)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a benign capillary vascular tumour of infancy. These lesions are common among children and are estimated to occur in 10% of all births. These lesions are often described as a painless red macule or papule (\u0022like a strawberry\u0022) and are most commonly present on the head and neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese lesions typically grow rapidly during the first few months of life, usually peak in growth around 9 - 10 months and then start to regress. The regression rate is about 10% per year, so that  over 95% will have vanished by the time the child turns nine years old. Unless the lesion causes some physical disability, the typical management includes reassurance (to parents and child) that the haemangioma requires no treatment and will usually spontaneously involute. High risk sites such close proximity to the nose, mouth or eyes might indicate some need for intervention. The differential diagnosis for strawberry haemangioma is a cherry haemangioma, which is found in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParental education should include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInformation about the natural course\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotential complications (e.g. cosmetic social implications, impairment of function in concerning locations like the eyelid)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications, risks and benefits and available treatment options\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERealistic expectations about the duration of involution and the possibility of residual changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObviously if the appearance of this haemangioma does start to cause problems for the girl, in terms of her self-esteem or social development then some form of active intervention could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn explanation for incorrect options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-blockers\u003C/strong\u003E (topical timolol or oral propranolol/atenolol) can be considered in the management of a strawberry haemangioma if the lesion has the potential to impair function or cause permanent disfigurement, as long as there are no cardiac or neurovascular concerns for the child. As there is insufficient data regarding the efficacy of beta-blockers in mild cases with no complications, active non-intervention is regarded as the best first-line approach for most cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a technique used for obtaining full-thickness skin specimens and is useful in the work-up of cutaneous neoplasms, pigmented lesions, inflammatory lesions and chronic skin disorders. As the diagnosis of strawberry haemangioma is made clinically, there is no indication for a punch biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShave biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a technique used for lesions that are predominantly epidermal without extension into the dermis, such as warts, papillomas, skin tags, superficial basal or squamous cell carcinomas, and seborrheic or actinic keratoses. As the diagnosis of strawberry haemangioma is made clinically, there is no indication for a punch biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is considered for involuted lesions with residual scars or loose skin; haemangiomas with inadequate involution by age four; pedunculated cutaneous hemangiomas (because of the risk of scarring); small, localised periorbital hemangiomas; slowly involuting lesions in cosmetically concerning locations. Due to the high rate of involution in most cases, a watchful waiting approach is indicated as first-line management in most haemangiomas without complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Strawberry haemangiomas are common lesions in childbirth and should be managed with reassurance, parental education and monitoring due to their high rate of spontaneous involution.","Beta-blockers and surgical excision can be considered under specific indications, but watchful waiting is still recommended as the first-line approach in strawberry haemangiomas with no complication."],"references":["Metry, D. (2021). Infantile hemangiomas: Management. UptoDate. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/infantile-hemangiomas-management?search=strawberry%20hemangioma%20children\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2~61\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2","Ryan, E. and Warren, L., 2012. Birthmarks Identification and management. Australian Family Physician, 41(5), pp.274-277."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94804"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1676"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15557"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15557"},"attributes